<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - world]]></title><link/> https://www.wsj.com/news/world <atom:link href="https://rsshub.app/wsj/en-us/world" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><description><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - world - Made with love by RSSHub(https://github.com/DIYgod/RSSHub)]]></description><generator> RS集线器</generator><webmaster>i@diygod.me (DIYgod)</webmaster><language> zh-cn</language><lastbuilddate> 2023 年 7 月 26 日星期三 12:33:26 GMT</lastbuilddate><ttl> 120 </ttl><item><title><![CDATA[Replaced, Then Erased: Mystery Deepens Around China’s Former Foreign Minister]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>外交部网站上几乎所有提及秦刚担任部长的内容都被删除，加剧了猜测<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001085354"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823935?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 5月23日在北京上映的秦刚已经从公众视野中消失一个多月了。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：托马斯·彼得/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001085354"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/wenxin-fan" itemprop="url" rel="author">范文欣</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 26 日上午 5:24 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/replaced-then-erased-mystery-deepens-around-chinas-former-foreign-minister-9117007a"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>香港——中国前外交部长在从公众视野中失踪一个多月后，于周二被接替，现在正在从外交部网站的部分内容中消失——这种删除加剧了人们对他遭遇的好奇心。</p><p>当局没有说明为何<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-foreign-minister-qin-gang-replaced-63660fad?mod=world_lead_pos5&amp;mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">决定免去</a>秦刚的职务，该职务目前已由他的前任王毅填补——至少是暂时的。外交部此前曾援引秦缺席的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-tries-to-reassure-u-s-amid-speculation-around-missing-foreign-minister-82697971?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">健康原因，但未具体说明原因</a>。</p><p>自从用王取代他以来，外交部已经从其官方网站上删除了几乎所有提及秦担任外交部长的内容。同样，在流行的社交媒体平台<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/WB" class="">微博</a>上<span class="company-name-type">，</span>有关秦最近担任职务的许多内容也从该部门的微博账户中消失了。</p><p>这些变化引起了<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/WB" class="company-name">微博</a>和中国互联网其他角落的关注，引发了对秦命运的热烈猜测。</p><p> “秦刚不是当过外交部长吗？”一位中国律师在微博上写道。 “网站处理此事的方式不合适。”</p><p>这位 57 岁的老人在担任中国领导人习近平精心挑选的外交部长不到七个月后，在外交队伍中<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-promotes-u-s-ambassador-to-foreign-minister-11672409545?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">的晋升速度异常迅速</a>。政治分析人士表示，秦的网上删除削弱了他因严重健康问题而被取代的观点。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=9F7AF9B6-88BC-4AB6-B4C8-E0CF0C68E116&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Freplaced-then-erased-mystery-deepens-around-chinas-former-foreign-minister-9117007a&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">北京在周二的紧急会议上重新任命最高外交官王毅接替秦刚担任外交部长，但没有提及秦刚神秘缺席的问题。中国领导人习近平七个月前亲自挑选了秦国。照片：Florence Lo/Pool 路透社/美联社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>“即使健康问题导致秦先生被免去外交部长职务，但这也没有理由导致他在外交部网站上过去的会议记录被删除，” <a href="https://chinamediaproject.org/2023/07/26/chinas-foreign-minister-is-removed-and-erased/" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">美国</a>媒体中国项目主任戴维·班志远（David Bandurski）写道。 <a href="https://chinamediaproject.org/2023/07/26/chinas-foreign-minister-is-removed-and-erased/" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">基础研究小组</a>。</p><p>在周三的例行新闻发布会上被问及这些变化时，外交部发言人毛宁表示，该网站正在按照协议进行更新。</p><p>围绕秦的戏剧性事件发生在北京和华盛顿的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-and-china-see-fragile-opportunity-to-repair-ties-8ad7ddff?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">微妙时刻</a>，因为两国最近才在紧张局势加剧之际重新建立高层沟通。政治分析人士表示，69岁的中共最高外交事务专家王岐山很可能被任命为临时替代者，为习近平和其他高级官员寻找更持久的解决方案争取时间。</p><p>美国国务卿安东尼·布林肯在访问太平洋岛国汤加时表示，他祝愿秦国一切顺利，并承诺将与王毅多次会面。</p><p> “我认识王毅也有十多年了，”布林肯说。 “我希望能够和他一起很好地合作，就像我们过去一样。”</p><p>政治分析人士表示，从长远来看，秦的接替不太可能破坏中美之间的外交，因为习近平制定了外交政策，尽管这凸显了<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-locks-information-on-the-country-inside-a-black-box-9c039928?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">中国政治体系日益不透明</a>。</p><p>周三在外交部网站上搜索秦的中文或英文名字没有结果。该网站的一份声明中，秦继续被列为外交部长，该声明称他代表中国于三月份与洪都拉斯建交。与已被删除的数百条其他声明不同，他的名字没有出现在洪都拉斯项目的标题中。</p><p>通过热门应用程序<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/TCEHY" class="company-name">微信</a>上的外交部官方账号搜索秦的名字，结果仍然是他担任外交部长期间的结果。描述秦以前担任副部长和驻美国大使的新闻仍然保留在外交部网站上。</p><p>官方媒体关于秦被免职的报道没有提到他作为国务委员的角色有任何变化，国务委员是中国内阁的高级政府职位。截至周三下午，内阁网站已更新，删除了对他部长职务的提及，但继续列出了他的其他头衔，包括作为共产党精英中央委员会成员的头衔。</p><p>中国的互联网审查机构对秦采取了选择性的方法。周三，微博将搜索结果隐藏在一些与他被删除相关的主题标签下，以及《寻秦记》的主题标签下，这是一部以中国古代秦朝为背景的奇幻电视剧。</p><p>但除此之外，用户还有空间继续猜测他失踪的原因，包括婚外情的可能性。</p><p> “这当然不是一次正常的工作调动，”一位微博用户写道，并对中国社交媒体上似乎无处不在的婚外情谣言表示认可。该帖子获得了超过 10,000 个赞。</p><p>写信给范文欣： <a href="mailto:wenxin.fan@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">wenxin.fan@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 26 Jul 2023 09:24:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/replaced-then-erased-mystery-deepens-around-chinas-former-foreign-minister-9117007a</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/replaced-then-erased-mystery-deepens-around-chinas-former-foreign-minister-9117007a<author><![CDATA[Wenxin Fan]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>微博</category><category>世界银行</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治</category><category>国内政治</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[What’s Happening in Israel? Protests and Strikes Over Netanyahu’s Judicial Overhaul]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>以色列领导人的举动导致国家分裂，引发大规模抗议，以下是您需要了解的情况<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823207/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="抗议者参加特拉维夫的示威活动。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>抗议者参加特拉维夫的示威活动。伊利亚·叶菲莫维奇/DPA/祖玛出版社<span>伊利亚·叶菲莫维奇/DPA/祖玛出版社</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0000724990"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0000724990"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/dov-lieber" itemprop="url" rel="author">多夫·利伯</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 26 日上午 3:52（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-protests-judicial-overhaul-netanyahu-7e264a71"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>耶路撒冷——近几个月来，数十万以色列人走上全国街头示威，反对总理本杰明·内塔尼亚胡政府计划的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israeli-doctors-go-on-strike-to-protest-netanyahus-judicial-overhaul-463530e7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">司法改革</a>。</p><p> 7 月 24 日，执政联盟推动以色列议会获得通过，这是该联盟希望通过的一系列<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-netanyahu-government-judicial-overhaul-protests-862dffd3?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">限制法院系统权力的</a>法律中的第一部。在达成妥协的谈判破裂后，该法案在没有任何反对派支持的情况下获得通过。反对派议员走出房间，抵制投票。</p><p>内塔尼亚胡是该国任职时间最长的总理，目前已进入第六个任期，在他的政府于三月份首次尝试通过另一套不同的法案后，内塔尼亚胡使司法立法从失败中恢复过来。在大规模抗议和大罢工导致国家瘫痪后，他<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/strike-called-flights-grounded-in-israel-over-netanyahus-judicial-overhaul-plan-e8c95930?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">推迟了这项努力</a>，但他在六月份表示，他将以修改后的形式通过这项改革。</p><p>该法律的通过标志着以色列社会的一个关键时刻，可能与该国最高法院摊牌，而该法律旨在遏制该机构的权力。对于数千名表示将退出的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israels-judicial-overhaul-raises-security-concerns-as-reservists-refuse-to-serve-5d68bfff?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">预备役军人</a>，以及威胁要大规模停工的商界、工会领导人和医疗专业人员来说，这是一个决定性的时刻。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=B58B7540-4CF9-464C-A04F-C0E71926FD01&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fisrael-protests-judicial-overhaul-netanyahu-7e264a71&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">以色列医生周二举行罢工，当局在因总理本杰明·内塔尼亚胡政府进行的司法改革而发生骚乱的夜晚，强行将抗议者从道路上带走。照片：阿米尔·利维/盖蒂图片社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>以色列最大的工会以色列总工会表示，他们正在为可能举行的总罢工做准备，一些抗议者正在敦促其采取这样的行动。然而，工会决定不在第一项法案通过后立即宣布大罢工。</p><p>第一项法案通过的第二天，以色列的医生和医务人员举行了罢工。</p><p>此次改革<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israeli-judicial-overhaul-pits-secular-religious-communities-against-each-other-a4177c16?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">引发了该国的分裂</a>，引发了美国等主要盟友的担忧，并在伊朗支持的真主党武装组织沿其北部边境造成的威胁日益加大的情况下，引发了对其军事准备情况的质疑。分析人士警告说，该国可能会陷入宪法危机。</p><p>这是您需要了解的内容。</p><h3>以色列民众为何抗议？</h3><p>在这个拥有 900 万人口的国家，每个周末都有多达 50 万以色列人出来抗议内塔尼亚胡<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/netanyahu-advances-overhaul-of-top-israeli-court-drawing-thousands-of-protesters-ee0287d7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">计划的对该国司法机构的改革</a>。</p><p>示威者和该国的政治反对派表示，该计划将削弱以色列本已脆弱的制衡体系，并破坏民主和对少数群体的保护。他们还表示，此次改革将对以色列的民主性格造成致命打击。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israels-right-wing-lawmakers-aim-to-remake-supreme-court-11668506325?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">关于以色列最高法院的争论</a>部分是由于该国自建国以来法律体系的模糊性造成的。以色列没有成文宪法。相反，法院的判决基于英国普通法、不断发展的以色列先例和一系列基本法，这些法律提供了准宪法的权力。</p><p>围绕最高法院的斗争也成为以色列社会更深层次裂痕的代表。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/story/why-israelis-are-protesting-netanyahu-governments-judicial-overhaul-0933acc5?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">抗议活动</a>使自由派、世俗的以色列人（他们将法院视为人权的保障者）与极端正统派以及宗教和政治保守派进行了对立，后者认为法院是实现其政策目标的障碍。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="839" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823210?width=1260&amp;height=839" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">议会通过司法改革提案的第一部分后，耶路撒冷的抗议者。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Orit Ben-Ezzer/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3>这场危机的核心是哪些司法变革？</h3><p>内塔尼亚胡的 64 名议员组成的整个联盟于 7 月 24 日投票赞成一项法律，该法律剥夺了最高法院撤销其认为“极其不合理”的政府决定的能力——他们认为这一概念含糊不清，并允许自由派法官推翻政府的意愿。越来越右翼的选民</p><p>这是联盟希望通过的一系列限制法院系统权力的法律中的第一部。接下来是一项法案，该法案将赋予立法者更多选择法官的权力，这一举措比周一通过的法案更具争议性。它可能会在秋季进行投票。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/netanyahu-revives-judicial-overhaul-stripped-of-most-controversial-piece-33160de" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">内塔尼亚胡六月告诉《华尔街日报》</a> ，他将放弃该计划在以色列以外地区最具争议的部分，这将赋予国家立法机构推翻最高法院裁决的权力。</p><p>所谓的“优先条款”将允许议会以 61 名议员的多数票否决最高法院有关立法的决定。这些提案还需要绝大多数法官才能推翻议会法律。批评者表示，拟议的改革实际上将结束对议会的司法审查，因为以色列历史上几乎每个议会联盟都拥有 61 个或更多席位。</p><h3>内塔尼亚胡为何推动司法改革计划？</h3><p>内塔尼亚胡三月份暂停了改革计划，并在大规模抗议后开始<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-calms-after-netanyahu-suspends-judicial-overhaul-b951d2c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">与反对派进行妥协谈判</a>。但在六月下旬，他表示双方未能达成协议，他将继续推进自己修改后的计划。</p><p>这位长期执政的领导人历来都不是改革司法制度的倡导者，但他面临着来自其联盟成员的巨大压力，要求他通过这一改革。联盟成员被广泛认为是该国75年历史上最右翼、民族主义和宗教色彩最浓厚的人。</p><p>关于司法立法的辩论揭示了以色列社会对于犹太国家和民主国家的意义的分歧。该国在成立之初的几十年里是由主要是东欧血统的世俗社会主义者建立和控制的。他们设想了一个文化上犹太教但社会上自由民主的国家。</p><p>近几十年来，代表以色列右翼的不同阶层——宗教犹太复国主义者、定居者、极端正统派和中东裔犹太人——之间的联盟在数量和力量上都在增长。内塔尼亚胡领导的利库德集团本身是世俗的，它已将这些右翼势力联合成一个政治强国。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823214?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">以色列总理本杰明·内塔尼亚胡在耶路撒冷举行的议会会议上。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：玛雅·阿莱鲁佐/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3>下一步是什么？</h3><p>非政府组织和其他组织已提交请愿书<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israels-supreme-court-could-strike-down-a-bill-aimed-at-limiting-its-power-but-will-it-cc17a8d7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">，要求以色列最高法院推翻该法律</a>，这类似于宪法修正案，取消了法院推翻其认为极其不合理的政府决定的权力。</p><p>最高法院从未做过这样的准宪法法律，但现在迫于公众压力却不得不这样做。</p><p>目前尚不清楚法院何时会对请愿书做出回应。下一步将是在法官面前举行初步听证会，然后法院可以决定将案件提交扩大法官席做出最终裁决。学者们表示，他们相信法院不会立即驳回此案。</p><p>以色列国家安全部长、该国极端民族主义右翼领导人伊塔马尔·本-格维尔表示，如果法院推翻这项法律，那将是“一场未遂政变”。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823222?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">以色列预备役军人在特拉维夫签署一份声明。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Matan Golan/SOPA/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3>这是否会影响以色列与美国的关系？</h3><p>尽管<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-ambassador-warned-israel-against-going-off-the-rails-with-judicial-overhaul-d612fffa?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">拜登政府一再发出警告</a>，内塔尼亚胡仍继续推进司法改革，其中包括在投票前几个小时，拜登总统发表公开声明，称该措施“正在变得更加分裂，而不是减少”。</p><p>在这些措施通过后，拜登政府官员很快坚称，正如白宫新闻秘书卡琳·让-皮埃尔所说，美以关系仍然“坚如磐石”。她没有直接回答有关是否会对以色列产生切实后果的问题，并将拜登描述为以色列的终生朋友。</p><p>分析人士表示，拜登不太可能试图通过削减对以色列的援助来惩罚内塔尼亚胡，国会也可能不会支持这一举措。但以色列政府不太可能完全避免为这次投票付出代价。</p><p>华盛顿智库大西洋理事会非常驻研究员卡米尔·阿尔比特表示：“这将为国会中的人士提供素材，尤其是那些想要向拜登政府施压，要求其重新考虑两国关系的左翼人士。” “我不认为这会威胁到两国关系，但随着时间的推移，它会削弱这种关系。”</p><p><em>本说明性文章可能会定期更新。</em></p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Shayndi Raice、David S. Cloud 和 Ari Flanzraich 对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给 Dov Lieber，邮箱为<a href="mailto:dov.lieber@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">dov.lieber@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 26 Jul 2023 07:52:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-protests-judicial-overhaul-netanyahu-7e264a71</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-protests-judicial-overhaul-netanyahu-7e264a71<author><![CDATA[Dov Lieber]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>卡琳·让-皮埃尔</category><category>卡米尔仲裁</category><category>本杰明·内塔尼亚胡</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Italy Says it Will Build the Longest Suspension Bridge in the World. Don’t Hold Your Breath.]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>连接西西里岛和意大利大陆的建筑计划已经存在了几十年<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821211/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="拟建的连接西西里岛和意大利大陆的单跨吊桥模型，该项目最初设想于 1860 年代。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>拟建的连接西西里岛和意大利大陆的单跨吊桥模型，该项目最初设想于 1860 年代。安杰洛·卡科尼/Shutterstock<span>安杰洛·卡科尼/Shutterstock</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001082304"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001082304"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/eric-sylvers" itemprop="url" rel="author">埃里克·西尔弗斯</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 26 日凌晨 3:46 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/italy-says-it-will-build-the-longest-suspension-bridge-in-the-world-dont-hold-your-breath-71b7cc86"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>意大利可能会建造世界上最长的吊桥。或者也许不会。</p><p>意大利政府重新点燃了政客们讨论了160年的一个想法： <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB1024343551810656360?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">在西西里岛和意大利大陆之间建造一座单跨吊桥</a>。横跨墨西拿海峡的两英里连接线将比世界上最长的吊桥长 50%，并将由两座塔楼支撑，每座塔楼都比<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/ESRT" class="">帝国大厦</a>的顶层还要高<span class="company-name-type">。</span></p><p>支持者，其中主要是意大利基础设施部长马泰奥·萨尔维尼表示，这将为<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/southern-italys-ills-test-shaky-national-coalition-11578139201?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">意大利萧条的南部</a>带来就业和经济增长，并将成为民族自豪感的源泉。但这个<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB120777463250502755?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">在 1860 年代最初设想</a>为促进民族团结的项目，如今已成为该国无法将空谈转化为行动的象征，或者至少无法一劳永逸地停止该项目。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="878" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/9f1f76f9-e0bf-4083-acd3-01cfe3507597-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>议会于五月批准了该计划。萨尔维尼承诺将于明年年中破土动工，并在 2030 年代初期投入运营。他对成本担忧不以为然，称意大利艺术家米开朗基罗、拉斐尔和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/IT/XMIL/LDO" class="company-name">达芬奇</a>的项目从未接受过议会成本效益分析。</p><p>除了成本之外，批评者还提到了环境影响、地震频发地区的地震风险以及黑手党可能夺取部分建筑合同的可能性。他们还表示，最好把钱花在升级西西里岛和卡拉布里亚（意大利靴尖地区）现有的破旧基础设施上。</p><p>意大利人认为这是似曾相识的感觉，这是情有可原的。</p><p> 20世纪50年代初，政府成立了一家公司来研究如何将西西里岛与大陆连接起来。四分之一个世纪后，该公司仍在考虑各种选择，从吊桥到隧道和悬挂的水下管道。一家新的政府支持的公司最终在吊桥上落户，然后在 2001 年，时任总理西尔维奥·贝卢斯科尼 (Silvio Berlusconi) 选择了一家承包商，但他在工程开始之前就失去了连任，在他的继任者的领导下，议会取消了该项目。</p><p>贝卢斯科尼<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/silvio-berlusconi-media-magnate-who-dominated-italian-politics-for-years-dies-at-86-98c096be?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">于 6 月去世，他</a>曾在 2011 年试图重启该计划，但第二年又被新政府取消，新政府称该计划在财政上不可持续，而<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052970204358004577028463184282238?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">意大利正面临主权债务危机</a>。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821209?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">基础设施部长马泰奥·萨尔维尼 (Matteo Salvini) 承诺，将在墨西拿海峡修建一座桥梁，并于 2030 年代初投入运营。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Gabriele Maricchiolo/NurPhoto/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>估计成本已从本世纪初的 50 亿欧元（约合 55.3 亿美元）飙升至现在的 135 亿欧元，其中不包括增加将桥梁与现有道路连接的必要基础设施的成本。政府对于从哪里获得这座大桥的资金一直含糊其辞。</p><p>基础设施部拒绝发表评论。在这座大桥获得议会最终批准的当天，萨尔维尼在推特上写道：“今天不仅对西西里岛和卡拉布里亚，而且对整个意大利来说都是伟大的一天。我为这一新成就感到自豪。”</p><p>这座桥最大的啦啦队长是最近才皈依的。 2017年，萨尔维尼表示，这笔钱最好用在更普通的基础设施上，例如改善国家的火车系统。他通过乘坐火车从西西里岛西海岸的特拉帕尼到该岛西南部的阿格里真托来表达自己的观点。乘坐几趟火车和一辆公共汽车花了 9 个小时才行驶了约 110 英里。</p><p>几十年来一直在这座桥上奋战的团体再次动员起来。上周，意大利最著名的环保活动团体之一 Legambiente 发布了一份名为“大虚张声势”的报告。海峡大桥的真相。”</p><p> Legambiente 西西里分会主席朱塞佩·阿尔菲里 (Giuseppe Alfieri) 表示：“我们需要开发一座桥梁的替代方案，利用技术创新来改善非洲大陆和西西里岛之间现有的铁路运输和渡轮服务。” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="1154" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/5d0b0f66-8fc4-4083-9de9-404e4b9813e0-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>在西西里岛和卡拉布里亚，超过 40% 的火车仍然使用柴油而不是电力，这使得火车总体上更清洁、更快、更可靠。西西里岛和卡拉布里亚的大多数火车线路只有一条轨道，这导致频繁的延误。</p><p>意大利并不是唯一一个实现永久循环大型基础设施梦想的国家。 300年来，泰国一直在讨论<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/for-centuries-thailand-has-dug-the-idea-of-a-canal-1437011519?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">修建一条连接太平洋和印度洋的运河</a>。在过去的 150 年里，英国偶尔会考虑用桥梁或隧道连接苏格兰和北爱尔兰，但这一想法从未通过可行性研究，部分原因是这座桥梁的估计成本为 3,350 亿英镑，相当于4,290 亿美元</p><p>墨西拿大桥的两座塔楼高 1,310 英尺，比金门大桥的塔楼高三分之一。这个高度使建筑商能够避免在墨西拿海峡中部建造一座塔，该海峡的水流强劲，会迅速远离海岸线。</p><p>慕尼黑工业大学工程与设计学院金属结构系主任马丁·门辛格 (Martin Mensinger) 表示：“主跨长度是一个挑战，但工程师们已经解决了这个问题。”他记得教授们对这座桥讨论了 30 多年。多年前，当他还是一名学生时。他说：“所谓的墨西拿桥面的特殊形状限制了风致振动引起的波动，并解决了如此大跨度桥梁的主要问题之一。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="816" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821206?width=1260&amp;height=816" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">意大利大陆西西里岛和卡拉布里亚之间的墨西拿海峡，拟议的桥梁将建在那里。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Maule/Fotogramma/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>虽然墨西拿海峡上仍然没有桥梁，但对最终结构进行的研究产生了新的墨西拿型甲板，该甲板而不是一个连续的甲板具有开口，可以让风通过并减少摇摆。</p><p>意大利基础设施部表示，这座桥将能够承受时速 170 英里的大风，高于该地区有记录以来的最强风力，并能承受 7.1 级地震，相当于 1908 年将墨西拿夷为平地的地震强度。这座桥每个方向都有3条车道、两条铁路线，宽约200英尺。它将位于海峡上方 200 多英尺处，允许大型船只从下面通过。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/IT/XMIL/WBD" class="">Webuild</a><span class="company-name-type">是</span>一家意大利总承包商，其领导的财团负责建造这座桥梁，该公司表示，一旦合同恢复，它可以在六年多一点的时间内完成该项目。 4月份，该公司工程负责人向议会委员会表示，将保证抗震能力达到7.5级。</p><p>土耳其 1915 年恰纳卡莱大桥于去年启用，是世界上最长的悬索桥，主跨度约为 1.3 英里，采用墨西拿型桥面板建造。</p><p>米兰理工大学机械工程系主任马可·贝洛利 (Marco Belloli) 表示：“恰纳卡莱大桥证实了墨西拿海峡的设计是可行的。”他专门研究风能，并进行了大量的风洞工作，以完善墨西拿海峡的设计。墨西拿桥。</p><p> “一百年前，你无法建造墨西拿大桥，但方法、材料和能力都得到了改善，”他说。 “现在可行了。”</p><p>写信给埃里克·西尔弗斯（Eric Sylvers）： <a href="mailto:eric.sylvers@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">eric.sylvers@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821210?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">意大利基础设施部长马泰奥·萨尔维尼（Matteo Salvini）展示了拟议跨越墨西拿海峡的桥梁模型。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：angelo carconi/Shutterstock</p></figcaption></figure></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 26 Jul 2023 07:46:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/italy-says-it-will-build-the-longest-suspension-bridge-in-the-world-dont-hold-your-breath-71b7cc86</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/italy-says-it-will-build-the-longest-suspension-bridge-in-the-world-dont-hold-your-breath-71b7cc86<author><![CDATA[Eric Sylvers]]></author><category> gfx-contrib</category><category>华尔街日报</category><category>重型建筑</category><category>桥梁建设</category><category>建造</category><category>房地产/建筑</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>伙伴关系/合作</category><category>公私合作伙伴关系</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>生活/生活方式</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>旅行</category><category>运输</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>伙伴关系</category><category>合作</category><category>公私伙伴关系</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>活的</category><category>生活方式</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>旅行</category><category>运输</category><category>重型建筑</category><category>桥梁建设</category><category>建造</category><category>房地产</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[It’s So Hot, They’re Growing Mangoes in Italy]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>地中海农民面临的问题预示着养活地球变暖所面临的挑战<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822900/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="Montserrat Sérvulo 矗立在西班牙埃布罗三角洲的稻田中，那里的大部分农作物被海水损坏。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Montserrat Sérvulo 矗立在西班牙埃布罗三角洲的稻田中，那里的大部分农作物被海水损坏。 <span></span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001081524"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001081524"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/margherita-stancati" itemprop="url" rel="author">玛格丽塔·斯坦卡蒂</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/matthew-dalton" itemprop="url" rel="author">马修·道尔顿</a></span>埃杜·拜尔 (Edu Bayer) 为《华尔街日报》拍摄的照片</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 26 日上午 12:02（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/its-so-hot-theyre-growing-mangoes-in-italy-55b97d58"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>西班牙埃布罗三角洲——大量的海水正在渗入这个珍贵的水稻种植区的稻田，蒙特塞拉特塞维洛正在考虑用海藻和蛤蜊替代至少部分农作物。</p><p> “这里的盐太多了，”这位 56 岁的农民站在田边说道，直到去年她还一直在这片田里种植水稻。现在这里已经长满了杂草和泥土。 “去年不是好年头，但至少我们有所收获。”</p><p>海平面上升、干旱和热浪<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/where-heat-waves-lead-food-inflation-will-follow-ee6a32c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">正在扰乱地中海地区的粮食生产</a>，该地区的饮食被视为文化瑰宝。</p><p>今年， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/europes-drought-deepens-threatening-agriculture-and-industries-caf3033d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">持续的干旱</a>和酷热对农业生产的打击尤其严重，从西班牙的橄榄园到阿尔及利亚的麦田都遭受严重破坏，导致产量下降，迫使农民考虑改种更耐寒的作物。</p><p>最近的热浪还以其他方式影响了粮食生产。据意大利农业贸易协会 Coldiretti 称，奶牛产奶量减少，蜜蜂采食花粉的意愿也降低，意大利的蜂蜜产量比去年下降了 70%。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="841" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822901?width=1260&amp;height=841" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">埃布罗三角洲的农田特别容易受到气候变暖的影响。 </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="841" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822902?width=1260&amp;height=841" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">现在，海水正在进一步向埃布罗三角洲的内陆推进，河流中没有足够的淡水来冲走稻田中多余的盐分。</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>地中海的气候变化速度比地球上大多数地方都快。自工业时代开始以来，这里的平均气温已经上升了约1.5摄氏度，高于除北极以外的所有其他地区。地中海地区农民所面临的问题预示着养活一个更热的星球所面临的挑战。</p><p>埃布罗三角洲的稻田面积约2万公顷，面临着海平面上升和干旱的双重压力，因此非常脆弱。</p><p>来自地中海的海水比以前更深入内陆，而埃布罗河没有足够的淡水来冲走田地里多余的盐分。由于长期干旱，今年河流干涸，三角洲供水首次出现长时间中断。</p><p>一些农民称，结果是他们所见过的最糟糕的收成。 “如果我们的收成能达到去年的 30%，那将是很多了，”Sérvulo 说，他种植的水稻品种用于制作啤酒、早餐麦片和当地特产西班牙海鲜饭。</p><p>短期解决方案包括处理更多废水和覆盖运河以限制水蒸发量。建立缓冲区以应对海岸侵蚀，例如通过人工海滩，也可能有所帮助。但这并不能解决所有问题。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="841" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822904?width=1260&amp;height=841" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">西班牙农业食品研究与技术研究所的科学家正在研究可以替代其他作物的海藻。</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> “在某些地区，水稻生产不再可行，”巴塞罗那研究中心 Eurecat 气候变化负责人卡莱斯·伊巴涅斯·马蒂 (Carles Ibañez Martí) 说道，他曾对埃布罗三角洲进行过研究。 “你可以在某种程度上对抗它，但适应是有极限的，到了某个时候你就无法再适应了，你必须改变。”</p><p>这个转折点有多近取决于海平面和气温上升的速度。在意大利北部的稻米产区，今年的干旱非常严重，一些农民已经种植了需要较少水的大豆。</p><p>科学家们并不乐观。联合国政府间气候变化专门委员会的最新报告称，全球变暖对地中海沿岸国家的影响在未来几十年可能会加剧。</p><p>西班牙加泰罗尼亚地区农业食品研究与技术研究所 IRTA 的科学家正在帮助农民适应气候变化，包括研究最适合取代埃布罗三角洲湿地稻田的鱼类、海藻和蛤品种。</p><p> “我们正在开发这项技术，以便在需要时可以轻松转让。我们需要从两到三年的生产周期中获得数据来向[农民]展示这是一个可靠、可行的机会。如果不这样做，他们将放弃这些地区，”负责 IRTA 水产养殖部门的恩里克·吉斯伯特 (Enric Gisbert) 说。 “这里发生的事情可能也会发生在地中海其他三角洲。”</p><p> IRTA 还开发了一种新品种的苹果，可以承受更高的温度。类似的研究也在其他地方进行。在以色列，研究人员最近开发了一种新品种的抗旱番茄。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="841" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822905?width=1260&amp;height=841" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">在埃布罗三角洲，种植水稻变得越来越具有挑战性。 </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="841" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822907?width=1260&amp;height=841" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">作为埃布罗三角洲适应气候变化的农业实践努力的一部分，正在试验不同的水稻品种和种植方式。</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>干旱给较为贫穷的地中海南缘地区带来了压力，那里的经济体被迫进口更多的小麦和其他主食。在阿尔及利亚和摩洛哥，该国地中海沿岸的小麦、大麦和其他主要农作物的田地在收获季节之前就已经变黄，因持续缺乏降雨而变得干燥。</p><p> “没有水。我们无法工作，”80 岁的穆罕默德·巴胡特 (Mohammed Bahout) 说。他的家人在阿尔及尔西部种植小麦和大麦，该地区位于海岸和阿尔及利亚高地之间，是该国的粮仓。他曾经种植西红柿和其他蔬菜，但由于缺水，他不得不种植耗水量较低的主要作物。</p><p> “如果仁慈的上帝不送水，我们就完了，”巴胡特说。</p><p>一些人正试图充分利用不断变化的气候。在意大利南部，农民正在种植芒果等热带水果。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          inline
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> 分享你的意见</h4><p><em>应采取哪些措施来保护世界粮食生产免受气候变化的影响？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> Coldiretti称，过去五年来，意大利香蕉、芒果和牛油果等水果的种植面积增加了三倍，目前覆盖意大利最南端的西西里岛、卡拉布里亚和普利亚地区约1,200公顷农田。</p><p>在意大利北部，温暖的天气促进了西红柿和橄榄油的大规模生产，直到 15 年前，这些作物还是半岛中部和南部地区的保护区。</p><p> “气温升高 1 或 1.5 摄氏度意味着我们现在可以在意大利北部种植小麦等作物。但如果气温上升之后出现大雨和冰雹，冰雹大小如网球，情况就会变得更加复杂，”Coldiretti 经济分析负责人洛伦佐·巴扎纳 (Lorenzo Bazzana) 表示。 “适应气候变化并不是那么简单。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=677BDE25-547F-4583-916F-61034C530B06&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fits-so-hot-theyre-growing-mangoes-in-italy-55b97d58&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">野火继续在希腊各地燃烧，迫使人们从热门的旅游岛屿科孚岛和罗德岛撤离。周末，罗德岛有 19,000 人被疏散。照片：Petros Giannakouris/美联社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>在法国南部的朗格多克葡萄酒之乡，数月的干旱和现在的热浪使葡萄园窒息。缺雨会使葡萄变小、枯萎，而高温会提高葡萄酒的酒精含量，并削弱风土特有的风味。</p><p>朗格多克位于西班牙附近的地中海沿岸，是法国最容易遭受高温和长期干旱风险的地区之一。</p><p> “我们很少见过这么长时间没有下雨的时期，”朗格多克葡萄酒种植者团体主席克里斯托夫·布斯克特(Christophe Bousquet)说。 “葡萄不太漂亮。它们的数量很多，但都非常小。”</p><p>朗格多克葡萄酒种植者正在寻找方法来保护他们的生计免受气候变化日益严重的影响。布斯凯在地中海地区的拉克拉普拥有一座葡萄园，他让草在他的葡萄藤周围生长，以便在下雨时保持土壤中的更多水分。</p><p>他们还在研究种植能够更好地抵御干旱和炎热的不同葡萄品种。布斯凯说，这是一个危险的改变，新的葡萄藤需要数年时间才能生长——他说他们没有时间。</p><p> “问题是，时间对我们不利，”他说。 “地中海气候的演变比预期的要快得多。”</p><p> —<em>何塞·包蒂斯塔对本文做出了贡献</em></p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822909?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">被海水破坏的蒙特塞拉特塞维洛田地的鸟瞰图。</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>写信给玛格丽塔·斯坦卡蒂<a href="mailto:margherita.stancati@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">（margherita.stancati@wsj.com</a> ）和马修·道尔顿（ <a href="mailto:Matthew.Dalton@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Matthew.Dalton@wsj.com</a> ）</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 26 Jul 2023 04:02:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/its-so-hot-theyre-grinding-mangoes-in-italy-55b97d58</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/its-so-hot-theyre-grinding-mangoes-in-italy-55b97d58<author><![CDATA[Margherita StancatiMatthew Dalton]]></author><category>华尔街日报</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>灾害/事故</category><category>干旱</category><category>自然灾害</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>天气</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>灾难</category><category>事故</category><category>干旱</category><category>自然灾害</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>天气</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Israel’s Supreme Court Could Strike Down a Bill Aimed at Limiting Its Power. But Will It?]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>公众压力迫使该国高等法院推翻限制其权力的法律<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001084207"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="591" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823613?width=860&amp;height=591" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">周二，在一项限制以色列最高法院权力的法案获得通过后，抗议者封锁了特拉维夫的一条高速公路。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Corinna Kern/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001084207"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/shayndi-raice" itemprop="url" rel="author">沙恩迪·赖斯</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 26 日上午 12:01 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israels-supreme-court-could-strike-down-a-bill-aimed-at-limiting-its-power-but-will-it-cc17a8d7"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>特拉维夫——反对总理本杰明·内塔尼亚胡司法改革的以色列人正在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-netanyahu-government-judicial-overhaul-protests-862dffd3?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">从街头向该国最高法院发起斗争</a>，要求法官废除本周颁布的一项引起分裂的法律。这个问题让全国震惊：他们会吗？</p><p>非政府组织和其他组织已提交请愿书，要求以色列最高法院推翻该法律，这类似于宪法修正案，取消了法院推翻其认为极其不合理的政府决定的权力。最高法院从未做过这样的准宪法法律，但现在迫于公众压力却不得不这么做。</p><p>耶路撒冷希伯来大学法学教授尤瓦尔·沙尼表示：“如果法院真的受理这些案件并推翻立法，那将是一场危机。”这种情况将使政府与法院对立，如果政府无视法院的裁决，可能会导致全面的宪法危机。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>六个多月来，数十万以色列人<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israeli-doctors-go-on-strike-to-protest-netanyahus-judicial-overhaul-463530e7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">抗议</a>内塔尼亚胡联盟对司法系统进行彻底改革的计划。由于无法通过抗议、罢工和预备役军人威胁拒绝服役来阻止这项立法，反对者现在希望最高法院介入。</p><p>以色列极右翼领导人、国家安全部长伊塔马尔·本-格维尔表示，如果法院推翻这项法律，这将是“一场未遂政变”。</p><p>目前尚不清楚法院何时会对请愿书做出回应。下一步将是在法官面前举行初步听证会，然后法院可以决定将案件提交扩大法官席做出最终裁决。学者们表示，他们相信法院不会立即驳回此案。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=B58B7540-4CF9-464C-A04F-C0E71926FD01&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fisraels-supreme-court-could-strike-down-a-bill-aimed-at-limiting-its-power-but-will-it-cc17a8d7&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">以色列医生周二举行罢工，当局在因总理本杰明·内塔尼亚胡政府进行的司法改革而发生骚乱的夜晚，强行将抗议者从道路上带走。照片：阿米尔·利维/盖蒂图片社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>该法案周一由以色列议会通过，是旨在限制法院权力并赋予立法者更多控制权的更广泛立法中的第一个。内塔尼亚胡的联盟表示，法院由激进的自由派法官控制，立法旨在恢复适当的权力平衡。反对者指责这项立法将削弱法院对行政和立法权的制衡作用，并将侵蚀以色列的自由民主。</p><p>周一通过的法律是对以色列一项基本法律的修正案，该法律是多年来零碎通过的，是以色列最接近宪法的法律。虽然以色列最高法院从未废除过一项基本法，但它表示它有权力这样做。</p><p>法律学者表示，请愿者必须证明几件事才能让法院推翻这项法律。反对者必须证明该法律破坏了以色列作为犹太民主国家的核心价值观。他们还可以试图证明立法程序存在缺陷。</p><p>以色列公民民主运动和达尔克努这两个向法院提交请愿书的非政府组织表示，该法律“对以色列民主的本质构成了严重和永久性的改变，这将摧毁民主政权所必需的制衡制度” ”。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823617?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">总理本杰明·内塔尼亚胡周一出席了在耶路撒冷举行的以色列议会会议。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：玛雅·阿莱鲁佐/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>耶路撒冷希伯来大学法学教授约夫·多坦 (Yoav Dotan) 表示，从表面上看，这项法律似乎是允许以色列议会颁布的。</p><p> “如果你从纯粹的法律理论角度来处理这个问题，那么就没有明确的宪法依据来推翻这项立法，”多坦说。</p><p>但多坦和其他学者表示，法院可以考虑这样的背景：该法案是更广泛的司法改革中的第一个法案，旨在通过消除强有力的制衡制度来破坏民主。司法改革的反对者声称，该计划的目的是限制法院对行政部门和立法部门进行制衡的能力，而在以色列，由于议会政治的性质，行政部门和立法部门的关系非常密切。</p><p>以色列赫兹利亚市赖希曼大学法学教授亚尼夫·罗兹奈 (Yaniv Roznai) 表示：“法院应该着眼于大局，因为当今的民主国家不会因一部表明我们不再是民主国家的法律而消亡。” “如今的民主国家是在一个渐进的过程中一步步消亡的。”</p><p>许多法律学者表示，法院更有可能削弱该法律的影响，而不采取严厉措施废除该法律。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823627?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">抗议者周一在耶路撒冷示威反对政府的司法改革。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Ronen Zvulun/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>例如，法院可以简单地将法案退回议会，称其需要进一步辩论和另一次投票。</p><p>法官还可以利用其解释权来限制法律的范围。法院在解释 2018 年基本法时采用了这种方法，该法将以色列定义为“犹太人民的民族家园”，批评者称该法歧视以色列的阿拉伯公民。法院表示，只要该法律不与其他确立人权的基本法相抵触，该法律就适用。</p><p>周一通过的法案称，法院不能推翻政府的决定，因为它“极其不合理”。法律学者表示，法院可以决定采用不同术语的类似标准，例如美国使用的任意性和反复无常，或欧洲使用的相称性。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>以色列最高法院应如何应对限制其权力的新法律？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> “法院不会废除这项法律，”多坦说。 “他们可以很容易地通过解释绕过该立法的大部分条款。”</p><p>罗兹奈表示，即使法院确实推翻了该法律，他也相信政府将遵守法院的裁决，以色列将避免真正的宪法危机。</p><p> “我无法想象以色列政府会违反这样的裁决，”他说。</p><p>写信给 Shayndi Raice，邮箱为<a href="mailto:Shayndi.Raice@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Shayndi.Raice@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 26 Jul 2023 04:01:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/israels-supreme-court-could-strike-down-a-bill-aimed-at-limiting-its-power-but-will-it-cc17a8d7</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/israels-supreme-court-could-strike-down-a-bill-aimed-at-limiting-its-power-but-will-it-cc17a8d7<author><![CDATA[Shayndi Raice]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Foreigners Will Benefit From U.S. Climate Subsidies, and That Is Good News]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>日韩企业的买入是成功的标志<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001085043"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="576" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822478?width=860&amp;height=576" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">今年早些时候，风力涡轮机在加利福尼亚州怀特沃特附近的一个风电场运行。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：马里奥·多摩/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001085043"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/nathaniel-taplin" itemprop="url" rel="author">纳撒尼尔·塔普林</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 26 日上午 12:01 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/foreigners-will-benefit-from-u-s-climate-subsidies-and-that-is-good-news-142e1ac1"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> Foreign firms are shaping up to be some of the biggest beneficiaries of America&#39;s new climate-focused industrial policy law, the Inflation Reduction Act. Japan&#39;s <a href="https://quotes.wsj.com/6752.TO">Panasonic</a> <span>,</span> for example, estimates it <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-biggest-winners-in-americas-climate-law-foreign-companies-c672e09d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">could reap $2 billion a year</a> from tax credits associated with battery plants in Nevada and Kansas.</p><p>那是问题吗？</p><p> Actually, it is a sign of success. It means the top firms in the global battery industry, including South Korea&#39;s <a href="https://quotes.wsj.com/066570.SE">LG</a> and Panasonic, see the American market opportunity as too large to pass up, even if that means building factories there instead of back home—and even though that also risks training local engineers and upstream contractors who could eventually emerge as powerful battery players in their own right.</p><p> China has used this strategy to great effect in industries it now dominates: Dangle a massive, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musk-is-feted-in-china-after-spurring-nations-ev-rise-d0357921?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">subsidized market opportunity</a> in front of technological leaders—think <a href="https://quotes.wsj.com/TSLA">Tesla</a> or, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musk-is-feted-in-china-after-spurring-nations-ev-rise-d0357921?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">&nbsp;</a> further back, Danish wind turbine maker <a href="https://quotes.wsj.com/VWS.KO">Vestas</a> —but require local production to access it. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823886?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> Chinese industrial policy, however, has come with big downsides too: Namely <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/fueled-by-long-credit-binge-chinas-economy-faces-drag-from-debt-purge-e4621859?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">heavy debt</a> and enormous waste. China spent at least 1.48% of its 2019 economic output on policies to support specific industries and firms, according to an analysis last year by Washington think tank the Center for Strategic and International Studies—mostly in the form of below-market credit to state-owned firms, tax incentives and direct subsidies. Adding in some policy tools idiosyncratic to China, like below-market land sales, raises the total to more than 1.7%.</p><p> To put that number in context, 1.48% of 2019 US output would be about $320 billion a year, in 2019 dollars. The <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/climate-legislation-inflation-reduction-act-small-towns-eb0ce798?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">new climate bill</a> itself only provides a total of about $400 billion in government support for energy and climate-related investments, including in manufacturing, according to the Congressional Budget Office—over 10 years. The CSIS authors estimate that the US only spent about 0.39% of gross domestic product on industrial policy in 2019.</p><p> To compete, the US will therefore need to use its own more limited funds much more wisely. That means learning from the current technological leaders rather than trying to reinvent the wheel at an astronomical cost—as China is currently trying to do in the chip sector, and as it tried to do early on in its EV effort.</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> A look at how that particular effort actually played out is instructive. China&#39;s EV industry is an export juggernaut now, but rewind five years—before Tesla&#39;s Shanghai gigafactory—and the story looked very different. A <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-has-487-electric-car-makers-and-local-governments-are-clamoring-for-more-1531992601?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Journal article from 2018</a> highlighted that China had 487 electric vehicle firms, many backed by local governments or by entrepreneurs with little or no automotive experience. Cheap state capital and protection from global competition in the form of onerous joint venture requirements and generous domestic-only subsidies proved too much to resist for many Chinese would-be EV gurus—including many who probably should never have been in the business to begin with.</p><p> Finally, in 2018 and 2019, Beijing tweaked the rules to allow Tesla to access subsidies and run a wholly-owned factory in China— <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musk-needs-china-china-needs-him-the-relationship-is-complicated-11638594026?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">with the express purpose</a> of building up local technical knowledge and supply chains—and bringing discipline to the bloated local industry. Now, in 2023, China&#39;s EV herd is about to thin fast, but it has also become the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/your-next-electric-vehicle-could-be-made-in-china-a288ab58?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">largest auto exporter</a> in the world.</p><p> China&#39;s recent EV success isn&#39;t solely due to that shift to a less “China first” style policy—global carmakers&#39; pandemic-era troubles were an important factor and several local firms have—with a bit more competition—proven themselves nimble and effective innovators. But there is little doubt that Tesla&#39;s presence—both as a competitor and investor—was a significant spur. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=AEFDD20E-B8EC-4F14-B1AA-8439E0D73B67&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fforeigners-will-benefit-from-u-s-climate-subsidies-and-that-is-good-news-142e1ac1&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Special Presidential Envoy for Climate John Kerry met with Chinese Premier Li Qiang in a visit aimed to try to revive stalled cooperation on climate change. Photo: Florence Lo/Reuters<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>And the costs of the previous strategy were substantial. China&#39;s local government debt burden has exploded over the past decade, in no small part due to an arms race among city governments to support local industrial policy champions in areas like solar, robotics, electric vehicles and microchips. Local governments&#39; debts and payables held through off balance sheet corporate vehicles roughly doubled from 2018 to 2022, reaching 59 trillion yuan ($8.4 trillion) according to a June note from Rhodium Group. Much of that is related to the property sector bust and endless Covid-19 restrictions during the pandemic years—but subsidies, often highly inefficient, running to nearly 2% of GDP, don&#39;t help either.</p><p> The US will need to be a player in key industries like electric vehicles and batteries in the decades to come if it wants to retain its perch as the world&#39;s top economy, as well as decarbonize without ceding too much leverage to potential adversaries. But to do that affordably, it will also need help—especially from the tech heavyweights of East Asia on China&#39;s periphery, who also happen to be American treaty allies.</p><p> Write to Nathaniel Taplin at <a href="mailto:nathaniel.taplin@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">nathaniel.taplin@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 26 Jul 2023 04:01:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/foreigners-will-benefit-from-us-climate-subsidies-and-that-is-good-news-142e1ac1</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/foreigners-will-benefit-from-us-climate-subsidies-and-that-is-good-news-142e1ac1<author><![CDATA[Nathaniel Taplin]]></author><category>计算机/消费电子产品</category><category>Personal Electronics</category><category>机动车</category><category>替代燃料汽车</category><category>汽车</category><category>消费类电子产品</category><category>技术</category><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>Government Aid/Grants</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>Heard on the Street</category><category> DJ Exclusive Analysis - All</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>特斯拉</category><category>TSLA</category><category> Panasonic Holdings</category><category> 6752.TO</category><category> JP:6752</category><category>松下</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>government aid</category><category>赠款</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>heard on the street</category><category> dj exclusive analysis - all</category><category>电脑</category><category>消费类电子产品</category><category>personal electronics</category><category> motor vehicles</category><category> alternative fuel vehicles</category><category>汽车</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[British Billionaire Joe Lewis Charged With Insider Trading]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Owner of Tottenham Hotspur tipped off pilots, lovers and associates, prosecutors said <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001084655"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="559" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823848?width=860&amp;height=559" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Joe Lewis faces 19 criminal charges, including securities fraud and conspiracy.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Mike Egerton/PA Wire/ZUMA Press </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001084655"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/corinne-ramey" itemprop="url" rel="author">Corinne Ramey</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Updated July 25, 2023 9:26 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/british-billionaire-joe-lewis-charged-with-insider-trading-58679562"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> British billionaire Joe Lewis was indicted on insider-trading charges Tuesday for allegedly sharing confidential information about companies in which he invested with personal assistants, romantic partners and his pilots.</p><p> The tips by Lewis, the owner of the English Premier League soccer club <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/an-unexpected-title-challenge-at-tottenham-starring-jose-mourinho-as-himself-11606993719?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Tottenham Hotspur</a> , allowed these friends and associates to reap millions in profits, prosecutors said. Lewis faces 19 criminal charges, including securities fraud and conspiracy.</p><p> David Zornow, a lawyer for Lewis, said his client had come to the US voluntarily to face the charges. “The government has made an egregious error in judgment in charging Mr. Lewis, an 86-year-old man of impeccable integrity and prodigious accomplishment,” Zornow said.</p><p> Damian Williams, the US Attorney for the Southern District of New York, said Lewis orchestrated a brazen insider-trading scheme by taking advantage of his access to corporate board rooms.威廉姆斯在一份声明中说：“他利用内幕信息来补偿他的员工或向他的朋友和爱人赠送礼物。”</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> From 2013 to 2021, prosecutors said, Lewis engaged in multiple schemes to violate securities laws, including through submitting false filings to the Securities and Exchange Commission. Lewis also learned confidential information about clinical trials, company announcements and company finances, which he then shared with associates, according to an indictment.</p><p> In one case, he provided his pilots loans of $500,000 each, then encouraged them to buy stock in oncology company <a href="https://quotes.wsj.com/MRTX">Mirati Therapeutics</a> before the news of a clinical trial became public, prosecutors said. “The Boss has inside info” and “knows the outcome” because “otherwise why would he make us invest,” one pilot, who isn&#39;t named, texted to a friend, the indictment says.</p><p> Lewis, who is one of the company&#39;s largest shareholders, also shared information about Mirati with a girlfriend, according to the indictment.</p><p> Mirati didn&#39;t respond to a request for comment.</p><p> Lewis was born in London in 1937. He is the founder of Tavistock Group, a holding company with investments including real estate, hotels and restaurants.据其网站称，该公司在 13 个国家拥有 200 多项投资。该网站称，他还拥有世界上最大的私人艺术收藏之一，其中包括巴勃罗·毕加索、亨利·马蒂斯和埃德加·德加的作品。据福布斯报道，刘易斯的净资产超过 60 亿美元。</p><p> Write to Corinne Ramey at <a href="mailto:corinne.ramey@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">corinne.ramey@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 26 Jul 2023 01:26:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/british-billionaire-joe-lewis-charged-with-insider-trading-58679562</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/british-billionaire-joe-lewis-charged-with-insider-trading-58679562<author><![CDATA[Corinne Ramey]]></author><category> wsj-usnews</category><category> fed legal</category><category> Corporate Crime/Legal Action</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>Insider Dealing</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>金融犯罪</category><category>欺诈罪</category><category>High Net Worth Individuals</category><category> Securities Fraud</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>Fed Legal</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> corporate crime</category><category>合法举动</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>insider dealing</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>犯罪</category><category>financial crime</category><category> fraud</category><category> high net worth individuals</category><category> securities fraud</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[McCarthy Says House on Track for Biden Impeachment Inquiry]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> &#39;I believe we will follow this all the way to the end,&#39; speaker says <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001082415"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823227?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> The White House has repeatedly denied allegations that President Biden benefited from his son&#39;s overseas business dealings.</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Manuel Balce Ceneta/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001082415"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/annie-linskey" itemprop="url" rel="author">Annie Linskey</a></span> and <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/david-harrison" itemprop="url" rel="author">David Harrison</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Updated July 25, 2023 9:17 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/kevin-mccarthy-says-house-on-course-to-impeach-biden-1ae4dbd4"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> WASHINGTON—House Speaker Kevin McCarthy (R., Calif.) signaled the House is on a clear course to pursuing an impeachment case against President Biden, citing <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hunter-bidens-messy-path-to-a-plea-deal-c22bd962?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">claims of corruption</a> tied to his son Hunter Biden&#39;s overseas business dealings.</p><p> “This is rising to the level of impeachment inquiry,” McCarthy said Monday night on Fox News. “I believe we will follow this all the way to the end, and this is going to rise to an impeachment inquiry the way the Constitution tells us to do this.”</p><p> In comment to reporters Tuesday, McCarthy emphasized the distinction between launching an inquiry and an actual impeachment vote. “An impeachment inquiry is allowing Congress to get the information,” he said.</p><p> McCarthy was reacting to various developments in Republican probes into Hunter Biden&#39;s business dealings in China, Ukraine and other countries, which GOP lawmakers allege also potentially benefited or were tied to President Biden, something the White House has repeatedly denied. Republicans <a href="https://www.grassley.senate.gov/imo/media/doc/fd_1023_obtained_by_senator_grassley_-_biden.pdf" target="_blank" class="icon none">recently released an FBI document</a> that detailed unsubstantiated claims that Ukrainian energy company Burisma hired Hunter Biden at his father&#39;s request and was making payments to the Biden family in exchange for political influence.</p><p> Democrats say the claims aren&#39;t credible and the White House has repeatedly said that the two men were never in business together. Rep. Jamie Raskin (D., Md.), the top Democrat on the House Oversight and Accountability Committee, called the claims “secondhand, years-old allegations.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823229?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Speaker Kevin McCarthy (R., Calif.) said Tuesday that the House is on track for an impeachment inquiry.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: J. Scott Applewhite/Associated Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The White House has maintained that President Biden wasn&#39;t involved in Hunter Biden&#39;s business affairs. Democrats say Republicans are engaged in baseless speculation about Biden in retribution for the two impeachments and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/judge-aileen-cannon-sets-may-2024-trial-date-for-trumps-documents-trial-eefddbae?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">criminal prosecutions</a> of former President <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/donald-trump">Donald Trump</a> , who <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/donald-trump-republican-presidential-rivals-criticism-39d476c5?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">is currently the front-runner</a> for the 2024 GOP presidential nomination.</p><p> “Their eagerness to go after [President Biden] regardless of the truth is seemingly bottomless,” tweeted White House spokesman Ian Sams. At a briefing Tuesday, White House press secretary Karine Jean-Pierre said: “We&#39;re not going to get into hypotheticals,” when asked about GOP efforts to impeach Biden.</p><p> The House Judiciary Committee has been investigating what Republicans <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/justice-department-probes-to-come-under-congressional-investigation-11673305905?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">portray as the weaponization</a> of the Justice Department and the FBI, while the House oversight committee has been focused on <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/republicans-seek-new-momentum-for-biden-family-investigations-e5848cea" target="_blank" class="icon none">the financial dealings of the president and his family</a> . Many Republicans are eager to impeach Biden, but such a move would carry political risks heading into the 2024 election if voters see the efforts as overreaching and divisive.</p><p> While some lawmakers including Rep. Marjorie Taylor Greene (R., Ga.) cheered the prospect of an impeachment probe, others were more cautious.</p><p> Rep. Chip Roy (R., Texas), a member of the conservative House Freedom Caucus, said he wanted to approach the prospect of impeaching the president carefully.</p><p> “We&#39;ve got to look at all the evidence and information and make the case,” he said. “I don&#39;t like to toss around impeachment without making the case.”</p><p> Rep. Richard Hudson (R., NC), who chairs the House GOP&#39;s campaign arm, said: “No one is seriously talking about impeachment right now.” He added, “If we get to the point where we think [impeachment] is in the cards then I think at that point we have to bring the American people along with us.”</p><p> The oversight panel plans to bring in Devon Archer, one of Hunter Biden&#39;s business associates, for a transcribed interview soon, according to Austin Hacker, a spokesman for the committee.</p><p> Last week, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/irs-employees-say-justice-department-hampered-hunter-biden-tax-probe-fe502a09?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">two IRS employees described</a> what they said were efforts by the Justice Department to impede the criminal investigation into Hunter Biden&#39;s taxes. Republicans have accused the Justice Department of giving Hunter Biden lenient treatment by allowing him <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hunter-bidens-guilty-plea-adds-to-president-bidens-re-election-headaches-1c556495?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">to plead guilty</a> to two misdemeanor tax charges and a chance to avoid prosecution on a separate gun offense.</p><p> Republicans have been pursuing President Biden on other fronts as well. Last month, Rep. Lauren Boebert (R., Colo.) <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/some-house-republicans-want-to-fast-track-biden-impeachment-push-b3728721" target="_blank" class="icon none">sought a quick vote</a> on impeaching Biden over his handling of <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/migrant-influx-overwhelms-southern-border-as-title-42-winds-down-da4e1e99?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">migrants at the border</a> . House Republican leaders were caught off guard and managed to beat back an impeachment vote by transforming it into a vote directing the Homeland Security Committee to initiate an investigation. That vote then passed along party lines.</p><p> The House would need just a simple majority to impeach a president. The matter would then head to the Senate, where a two-thirds supermajority would be needed to remove the president from office.</p><p> Trump <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/house-prepares-to-vote-on-impeaching-trump-11576667768" target="_blank" class="icon none">was impeached in late 2019</a> for pressuring Ukraine to investigate the Biden family by using aid as leverage, and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-to-face-impeachment-vote-over-capitol-riot-11610543781" target="_blank" class="icon none">was impeached again in early 2021</a> for his actions related to the Jan. 6 Capitol riot.</p><p> Earlier this month, federal prosecutors informed Trump <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/donald-trump-jack-smith-jan-6-letter-classified-documents-hearing-e679b87" target="_blank" class="icon none">he was a target of their investigation</a> into his efforts to overturn the election.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Tim Hanrahan and Sadie Gurman contributed to this article.</p><p> Write to Annie Linskey at <a href="mailto:annie.linskey@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">annie.linskey@wsj.com</a> and David Harrison at <a href="mailto:david.harrison@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">david.harrison@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 26 Jul 2023 01:17:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/kevin-mccarthy-says-house-on-course-to-impeach-biden-1ae4dbd4</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/kevin-mccarthy-says-house-on-course-to-impeach-biden-1ae4dbd4<author><![CDATA[Annie LinskeyDavid Harrison]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>腐败</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>金融犯罪</category><category>Impeachment</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Hunter Biden</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>腐败</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>financial crime</category><category> impeachment</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Israel in Political and Economic Tumult; Doctors Strike, Stocks Tumble]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>反对总理司法改革的抗议运动领导人发誓将继续反对立法<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001081582"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
