"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=B58B7540-4CF9-464C-A04F-C0E71926FD01&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fisraeli-doctors-go-on-strike-to-protest-netanyahus-judicial-overhaul-463530e7&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">以色列医生周二举行罢工，当局在因总理本杰明·内塔尼亚胡政府进行的司法改革而发生骚乱的夜晚，强行将抗议者从道路上带走。照片：阿米尔·利维/盖蒂图片社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001081582"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/dov-lieber" itemprop="url" rel="author">多夫·利伯</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 25 日下午 1:01（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israeli-doctors-go-on-strike-to-protest-netanyahus-judicial-overhaul-463530e7"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>特拉维夫——总理本杰明·内塔尼亚胡开始改革<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-netanyahu-government-judicial-overhaul-protests-862dffd3?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">司法系统</a>后，以色列人准备迎接新的政治和经济动荡时期，医生罢工，股市和货币下跌，抗议者发誓要继续大规模示威。</p><p>经过一晚的抗议活动后，以色列人等待周一通过的这项旨在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/netanyahu-revives-judicial-overhaul-stripped-of-most-controversial-piece-33160de?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">限制最高法院权力</a>并赋予立法者更多权力的立法的影响，全国局势紧张。已经向高等法院提交了请愿书，要求其废除该法律，此举可能引发宪法危机。他们还在观望，如果法案通过，数千名威胁将拒绝报到的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israels-judicial-overhaul-raises-security-concerns-as-reservists-refuse-to-serve-5d68bfff" target="_blank" class="icon none">预备役军人</a>是否会信守诺言。他们目睹了经济似乎因<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-protests-judicial-overhaul-netanyahu-7e264a71" target="_blank" class="icon none">政治戏剧</a>的上演而陷入短暂的冲击。</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>该法律的通过标志着以色列社会的一个关键时刻，以色列社会分为两部分：一大部分是世俗以色列人，他们担心这项立法会破坏该国的自由民主；另一部分则是<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-ultra-orthodox-haredim-military-service-supreme-court-of-ultra-orthodox-jews-shakes-israels-sense-of-identity-b3155e01?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">宗教和极端民族主义选民</a>，他们认为法院由自由派法官主导，而这些人经常推翻法院的判决。人民的意志。</p><p>以色列主要股市指数 TA-35 自周二开盘以来下跌超过 3%。过去一个月，以色列股市一直呈上升趋势，希望能够就立法达成妥协。周二，以色列货币谢克尔兑美元汇率下跌 1.3%。</p><p>以色列最大的投资公司之一梅塔夫投资公司(Meitav Investment House)的首席经济学家亚历克斯·扎贝任斯基(Alex Zabezhinsky)表示，谢克尔兑美元的价值在很大程度上反映了美国股市的情况，直到今年年初司法改革立法首次公布，此后一直如此。已断开连接。</p><p> “超过10%的贬值是政治骚乱的结果，”他说。他说，如果没有国内动荡，其价值应在 1 美元兑换 3.3 谢克尔左右。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="700" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823966?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p><a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/MS" class="company-name">摩根士丹利</a>表示，将以色列的主权信用评级下调至“不喜欢的立场”。穆迪投资者服务公司表示，该法案的通过表明以色列的社会和政治紧张局势将持续“对以色列的经济和安全局势产生负面影响”。</p><p>内塔尼亚胡和财政部长贝扎雷尔·斯莫特里奇在一份联合声明中表示：“这只是暂时的反应，当尘埃落定后，就会清楚地看到以色列的经济非常强劲。”</p><p>两人指出了以色列日益增长的天然气工业、英特尔<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israels-netanyahu-touts-expanded-investment-by-intel-amid-tech-backlash-e0bdbfe6?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">最近向该国投资 250 亿美元</a>以及<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/NVDA" class="company-name">Nvidia</a>的选择</p>在以色列建造一台超级计算机等，作为以色列强劲经济的证据。<p></p><p>声明称：“以色列经济有着强劲的基本面，并将在经验丰富的领导层以及制定负责任的经济政策的领导下继续增长。”</p><p>四月份，穆迪警告说，政府的计划可能会损害该国的经济前景。该机构重申了以色列的 A1 评级，但将其前景从积极调整为稳定，这表明未来可能会下调该国的评级。</p><p>网络安全初创公司 AxoniusX 首席执行官阿米尔·奥菲克 (Amir Ofek) 表示：“很明显，投资者将会产生疑问和疑虑——当以色列的环境不再可预测时，为什么还要投资以色列。” “很明显，作为以色列人，我们只是在搬起石头砸自己的腿。”</p><p>代表高科技工人的抗议团体在五家主要报纸上刊登了全黑版的头版广告。另一边，广告上写着“以色列的引擎永远不会放弃”。以色列<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israeli-startups-struggle-to-raise-money-amid-political-turmoil-global-downturn-52703ac1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">科技行业</a>一直处于反对该立法的最前线。许多科技工作者认为，此次改革将破坏民主和对该国法院系统的信心，这可能会吓跑投资者和人才。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823096?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">一名抗议者在耶路撒冷议会附近举行示威活动时举着以色列国旗。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：阿米尔·利维/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>“这很好地代表了我们的感受，”说</p>支付公司 Papaya Global 的首席执行官 Eynat Guez 拍摄了高科技工人拍摄的广告。盖兹表示，她希望市场反应和来自银行的负面情绪能够促使内塔尼亚胡和他的政党中的其他人“清醒过来……否则他们将作为毁灭以色列的人而被载入史册。”<p></p><p>以色列高度依赖其技术部门，该部门占该国国内生产总值的 15%，占出口额的一半左右。近几十年来，该国不断繁荣，吸引了外国投资，推动了<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tech-boom-floods-israels-silicon-valley-with-cash-exposing-divisions-11632562536?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">初创企业和科技公司的爆炸式增长</a>。许多以色列科技公司的总部或员工都居住在特拉维夫地区，这是以色列世俗和自由派的基地，大规模示威活动已连续 29 周发生。</p><p> Bessemer Venture Partners 驻以色列合伙人 Adam Fisher 表示，该法案的通过不会对以色列科技公司产生明显而直接的影响，但会导致更多员工选择迁出以色列。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823452?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> “这对国家来说是损失，但对以色列高科技来说不一定是损失，”他说。</p><p>周一通过的法案剥夺了最高法院撤销其认为“极其不合理”的政府决定的能力，这是法院用来确保政府在做出适当考虑的情况下做出决定的标准。这包括雇用和解雇重要的政府任命，例如政府部长、总检察长和安全部门负责人。</p><p>自该法案通过以来，已经向高等法院提交了几份请愿书，试图推翻该法案。尽管法院从未否决过像周一通过的法案这样的法案（相当于宪法修正案），但以色列宪法学者表示，法官们认为法院可以拥有这样的权力。</p><p>以色列国家安全部长伊塔马尔·本-格维尔表示，最高法院否决该法案的举动将被视为“未遂政变”。</p><p>以色列医学协会表示，之所以发起此次罢工，是因为新法律取消了对卫生部政治领导层的司法审查，称这将“对卫生系统、患者和医生造成严重后果”。该协会表示，它已游说政府继续对卫生系统进行司法审查。</p><p> “医疗系统是以色列许多其他地方所不存在的独特生态系统。它让不同部门的人们能够为了共同利益而和平合作，”38 岁的特拉维夫老年病学家亚伦·比莱克 (Aaron Bilek) 表示，他参加了罢工。 “感觉庇护所受到威胁真的很可怕。”</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Ari Flanzraich 对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给 Dov Lieber，邮箱为<a href="mailto:dov.lieber@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">dov.lieber@wsj.com</a></p><p id="correction" class="correction"> <strong>Corrections &amp; Amplifications</strong><br> The currency chart in the story shows how many Israeli shekels one dollar buys. A previous version of the chart showed the data in reverse and incorrectly described the data as showing how many Israeli shekels one US dollar buys. (Corrected on July 26)</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 25 Jul 2023 17:01:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/israeli-doctors-go-on-strike-to-protest-netanyahus-judicial-overhaul-463530e7</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/israeli-doctors-go-on-strike-to-protest-netanyahus-judicial-overhaul-463530e7<author><![CDATA[Dov Lieber]]></author><category>以色列</category><category>gfx-contrib</category><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>内乱</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>社会问题</category><category>军事行动</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>内乱</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>社会问题</category><category>军事行动</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Stuck on a Flight? Know Your Rights During a Tarmac Delay]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>如果恶劣天气或飞机拥堵导致您滞留在跑道上，以下是您作为航空公司乘客的权利<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821700/?width=2000&amp;size=1.5" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>乔恩·克劳斯 (Jon Krause) 的插图<span>乔恩·克劳斯 (Jon Krause) 的插图</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001073822"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001073822"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/allison-pohle" itemprop="url" rel="author">艾莉森·波尔</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 25 日中午 12:13（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tarmac-delay-rights-airports-9c5b1464"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>今年夏天，对于美国旅行者来说，计划外的停机坪时间变得令人沮丧地司空见惯。</p><p>有关停机坪延误的联邦数据滞后三个月，但经验丰富的旅客表示，他们观察到全国主要机场停机坪上的等待时间很长。在典型的停机坪延误中，飞机要么到达并需要等待登机口，要么在飞机舱门关闭后等待起飞。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/flight-cancellations-and-delays-mount-as-thunderstorms-hit-east-coast-c11c9161?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">恶劣的天气</a>给航空公司的运营带来了压力，并导致停机坪延误。天气问题导致飞机起飞延迟，并导致抵达飞机的可用登机口短缺。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/united-airlines-newark-flights-cut-9f5f57f6?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">纽约地区机场的</a>延误情况非常明显。运营机场的纽约和新泽西港务局表示，当天气恶化时，出发和到达的时间会更加间隔。航空公司高管还表示<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/faa-tries-to-ease-flight-congestion-at-new-york-airports-933d1da0?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">，空中交通管制员的短缺</a>加剧了挑战。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> “没有人对机场延误感到高兴，这就是为什么我们正在与合作伙伴密切合作，以减少停机坪延误，而停机坪延误很大程度上是由纽约/新泽西地区和目的地机场最近的恶劣天气造成的。”港务局发言人在一封电子邮件中说道。</p><p>十多年前，交通部实施了一项禁止停机坪长时间延误的规定。如果航空公司让乘客在飞机上停留的时间超过交通部规定的时间且没有机会下机，他们可能会面临罚款。航空分析师表示，这一规定大大减少了乘客在飞机上滞留数小时的事件数量。但航班延误仍然时有发生——交通部对停机坪延误的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/united-airlines-is-fined-1-9-million-for-runway-delays-11632516201?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">航空公司处以罚款</a>，其中包括 2021 年对<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/UAL" class="company-name">美国联合航空公司 (United Airlines)</a>的 190 万美元罚款。</p><p> 7月17日<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/DAL" class="company-name">，达美航空一架</a>从拉斯维加斯飞往亚特兰大的航班在地面上滞留了大约三个小时，而室外温度却高达110多度。</p><p> Tashina 和 Janssen Robinson 与他们 16 岁的侄女和 1 岁的婴儿一起乘坐飞机。住在亚特兰大的罗宾逊一家在家庭团聚后乘飞机回家，他们说飞机上的空调已经打开。但塔西娜说，微弱的气流感觉就像“在阳光下吹风扇”。</p><p>交通运输部正在调查这起事件。达美航空表示正在配合调查，并正在调查导致机上温度不舒服的原因。</p><p>交通部针对这些情况制定<a href="https://www.transportation.gov/individuals/aviation-consumer-protection/tarmac-delays" target="_blank" class="icon none">了消费者保护措施</a>，尽管这些保护措施可能有限。以下是关于停机坪延误期间您的权利的信息。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="444" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822623?width=700&amp;height=444" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> DOT 规则要求航空公司在国内航班延误超过 3 小时、国际航班延误超过 4 小时之前开始转移到乘客可以离开的地方，但有一些例外。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Kena Betancur/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3>为什么飞机会卡在停机坪上？</h3><p>联邦航空管理局前高级管理人员、佛罗里达州安柏里德尔航空大学助理教授迈克尔·麦考密克表示，阻碍飞机起飞的天气是地面延误的主要原因之一。</p><p>由于空中交通管制员正在努力减少恶劣天气地区的拥堵，因此距离风暴系统数百英里的乘客可能会遇到地面延误。麦考密克说，严重且频繁的雷暴切断了飞机的航线。当航班无法起飞时，没有足够的登机口供抵达的飞机停放。人员配备或机械问题也可能导致延误。</p><p>纽约机场有限的跑道容量加剧了天气和空中交通管制问题</p>保罗·哈德森 (Paul Hudson)，消费者权益保护组织 FlyersRights 的总裁。<p></p><p>港务局表示，正在对其机场进行投资，包括机场滑行道，以帮助飞机更快地进出跑道。</p><h3>我的航空公司是否因停机坪延误而欠我赔偿？</h3><p>不可以。但他们必须在停机坪延误开始后两小时内为您提供零食和水。即使延误持续很长时间，他们也不需要提供餐点。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>今年夏天您的航空旅行经历如何？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>航空公司必须为可能需要的人提供工作厕所、舒适的机舱温度和医疗护理。没有定义为舒适的设定温度。</p><p>如果您的航班在停机坪延误后延误或取消，您可能需要赔偿。一些航空公司会为因延误或取消而导致的食品、酒店或地面交通提供代金券——只要延误或取消是在他们的控制范围内。 （与天气相关的问题不适用。）</p><h3>航空公司可以让乘客在飞机上停留多长时间？</h3><p>对于国内航班，交通部规则要求航空公司在延误超过三小时之前开始转移到乘客可以离开的地方。这适用于抵达和出发。对于国际航班，时间限制为四个小时。但出于安全、安保和空中交通管制相关原因，它允许例外。</p><p>麦考密克说，例如，如果您的飞机在 30 架飞机的队列中排名第四，那么脱离队列并返回登机口可能会被视为对空中交通运营的干扰。</p><h3>如果我的飞机被困在停机坪上该怎么办？</h3><p>在您有机会下飞机之前，您的选择是有限的。如果您选择在停机坪延误期间下机，航空公司不需要让您重新登机，您可能需要寻找其他航班。</p><p>麦考密克说，无法保证您下飞机后会与行李重聚。</p><p>哈德森说，这些天飞机已经满员，这意味着无法保证您能搭乘下一班航班。</p><p><em>这篇文章可能会更新</em>。</p><p><em>订阅新的</em> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/newsletters?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none"><em>《华尔街日报》旅游通讯，</em></a><em>了解《华尔街日报》旅游团队的更多提示和见解。</em></p><p>写信给 Allison Pohle，邮箱为<a href="mailto:allison.pohle@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">allison.pohle@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 25 Jul 2023 16:13:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/tarmac-delay-rights-airports-9c5b1464</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/tarmac-delay-rights-airports-9c5b1464<author><![CDATA[Allison Pohle]]></author><category> WSJ生活工作</category><category>航空公司</category><category>客运航空公司</category><category>机场</category><category>航空运输</category><category>运输/物流</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>运输</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>联合航空控股</category><category>伦敦大学艺术学院</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>运输</category><category>航空公司</category><category>客运航空公司</category><category>airports</category><category>航空运输</category><category>运输</category><category>后勤</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[China’s Foreign Minister Replaced After Unexplained Absence]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Qin Gang is removed months after Xi Jinping promoted him to head the Foreign Ministry <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001081700"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=9F7AF9B6-88BC-4AB6-B4C8-E0CF0C68E116&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fchina-foreign-minister-qin-gang-replaced-63660fad&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Beijing reappointed top diplomat Wang Yi to replace Qin Gang as foreign minister during an emergency session on Tuesday, without addressing Qin&#39;s mysterious absence. Photo: Florence Lo/Pool Reuters/Associated Press<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001081700"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/chunhan-wong" itemprop="url" rel="author">Chun Han Wong</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Updated July 25, 2023 10:15 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-foreign-minister-qin-gang-replaced-63660fad"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> SINGAPORE—Chinese leader Xi Jinping removed his <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/replaced-then-erased-mystery-deepens-around-chinas-former-foreign-minister-9117007a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">handpicked foreign minister</a> after less than seven months on the job, a surprise move that leaves more questions than answers around <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-shakes-up-government-as-xi-asserts-more-control-over-policy-ffc22275?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">China&#39;s black-box political system.</a></p><p> Qin Gang&#39;s removal comes after his <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-tries-to-reassure-u-s-amid-speculation-around-missing-foreign-minister-82697971?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">mysterious absence</a> from the public stage over the past month, a disappearance that has sparked speculation about his fate and cast a global spotlight on the Communist Party&#39;s opaque governance of the world&#39;s second-largest economy.</p><p> At a hastily convened session Tuesday, the Chinese legislature&#39;s standing committee decided that Wang Yi, the former foreign minister and currently China&#39;s top diplomat, would retake his old post, which he had relinquished late last year.</p><p> The lawmakers didn&#39;t provide a reason for their decision to remove the 57-year-old Qin, who had succeeded Wang after enjoying an unusually rapid rise through the foreign-service ranks in recent years. Qin&#39;s absence from major diplomatic engagements since late June had <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-tries-to-reassure-u-s-amid-speculation-around-missing-foreign-minister-82697971?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">fueled rumors inside and outside China</a> about what happened to him.</p><p> China&#39;s Foreign Ministry previously cited health reasons for Qin&#39;s absence from a regional diplomatic meeting in Indonesia earlier this month. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823226?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Wang Yi &#39;s return as foreign minister appears to be an interim appointment, analysts say.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: BERNADETT SZABO/REUTERS</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Wang, a 69-year-old member of the Communist Party&#39;s elite 24-member Politburo, served as foreign minister from early 2013 until December last year. He became China&#39;s top diplomat when he joined the Politburo in October as its leading foreign-affairs specialist.</p><p> In China&#39;s political system, the foreign minister isn&#39;t necessarily the country&#39;s highest-ranking diplomat. That role resides with the most senior foreign-policy official by party rank, who is currently Wang, the director of the office of the party&#39;s Central Foreign Affairs Commission.</p><p> State media reports didn&#39;t mention any change to Wang&#39;s party roles, suggesting he would occupy his Politburo and Foreign Ministry positions concurrently—an arrangement that, after the 1990s, has only taken place during a transition period between officeholders.</p><p> Political analysts say Wang&#39;s return as foreign minister appears to be an interim appointment to buy time while Xi and other senior officials figure out longer-term arrangements. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823223?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Qin Gang working in Cairo earlier this year.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Amr Nabil/Associated Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> “Qin&#39;s removal shouldn&#39;t be interpreted as a diminishment of Xi Jinping&#39;s power, which extends far wider and deeper than any one single appointment,” said Jude Blanchette, a China analyst at the Washington-based Center for Strategic and International Studies. “And the fact that, for now, Qin keeps some of his party and government positions indicates that there are some unresolved internal issues.”</p><p> State media readouts from Tuesday&#39;s session of the National People&#39;s Congress standing committee didn&#39;t mention any change to Qin&#39;s role as state councilor, a senior government rank in the State Council, China&#39;s cabinet. The State Council&#39;s website continued to list Qin as a state councilor as of Tuesday evening.</p><p> Party authorities haven&#39;t announced any change to Qin&#39;s status as one of 205 full members of the party&#39;s Central Committee, which he joined in October while he was China&#39;s ambassador to the US</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> Tuesday&#39;s legislative session was arranged just one day in advance, an unusually short notice, and outside the typical two-month cycle for regular standing committee sessions. This extraordinary session came right after a Politburo meeting on Monday, chaired by Xi.</p><p> “Overall foreign policy won&#39;t likely change in the wake of Qin&#39;s removal, as his role was simply to implement key decisions made by Xi Jinping,” said Blanchette.</p><p> The mystery around Qin has prompted new questions about China&#39;s governance under Xi, whose Communist Party has doubled down on its penchant for secrecy and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-locks-information-on-the-country-inside-a-black-box-9c039928" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">frustrated outsiders&#39; efforts</a> to access information about developments in a leading economic powerhouse.</p><p> Considered a <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-promotes-u-s-ambassador-to-foreign-minister-11672409545?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">trusted aide to Xi</a> , Qin had enjoyed an unusually rapid rise within China&#39;s foreign service in recent years after serving as protocol chief for the Chinese leader. Qin was appointed Beijing&#39;s ambassador to Washington in 2021 despite having no formal background directly handling US relations, before joining the Central Committee and winning promotion to foreign minister late last year—bucking precedent in a system that traditionally has valued experience in addition to political connections.</p><p> Political analysts say Qin&#39;s close association with Xi has made his absence particularly intriguing. A dearth of information about Qin&#39;s whereabouts has fueled speculation on social media, including around the possibility of an extramarital affair.</p><p> The Chinese Foreign Ministry first addressed Qin&#39;s disappearance on July 11, when it said at a regular news briefing that he wouldn&#39;t attend an international gathering of foreign ministers in Jakarta because of health reasons, without giving any details. Since then, the ministry&#39;s spokespeople have generally sidestepped questions about Qin.</p><p> In China&#39;s opaque political system, health issues are often cited as the reason for a senior official&#39;s absence. While the explanation is often genuine, party insiders say, it can sometimes serve as cover for political problems.</p><p> When Wang Lijun, the former police chief in the inland megacity of Chongqing, went missing in February 2012, municipal authorities said he was taking “vacation-style treatment” for stress and overwork, though in reality he had fled to the US consulate in the nearby city of Chengdu to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10000872396390444100404577643450001423304" target="_blank" class="icon none">seek asylum</a> .</p><p> Beijing&#39;s move to replace Qin as foreign minister won&#39;t quell speculation around his fate, since it leaves many questions about what caused his prolonged absence, said Alfred Wu, an associate professor at the Lee Kuan Yew School of Public Policy in Singapore.</p><p> At Tuesday&#39;s legislative session, lawmakers also named Pan Gongsheng as governor of the People&#39;s Bank of China. The move had been expected after the 60-year-old Pan, who had been deputy governor since 2012, was <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-plans-to-appoint-a-new-central-bank-governor-56a878ea" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">appointed as the central bank&#39;s top party official</a> earlier this month.</p><p> The veteran economist and banker had been <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-man-charged-with-steering-the-yuan-through-chinas-economic-turmoil-37574af8" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">getting ready to retire</a> in the weeks before Xi picked him to lead the central bank at a time when the Chinese yuan has been on a downward slide, The Wall Street Journal has reported.</p><p> Write to Chun Han Wong at <a href="mailto:chunhan.wong@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">chunhan.wong@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 25 Jul 2023 14:15:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-foreign-minister-qin-gang-replaced-63660fad</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-foreign-minister-qin-gang-replaced-63660fad<author><![CDATA[Chun Han Wong]]></author><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治</category><category>国内政治</category></item></channel></rss>